    (2,"easy","Electoral Photo Identity Card (EPIC) ఏ year introduce అయింది? / In which year was EPIC (Voter ID) introduced?",
     "1977","1993 — ECI (under T.N. Seshan) introduced Electoral Photo Identity Card (EPIC) from 1993; not mandatory for voting but used as proof of voter identity; all voters enrolled in electoral roll get EPIC","2000","2004","b",
     "EPIC (Electoral Photo Identity Card): Introduced by ECI in 1993 under CEC T.N. Seshan. Photo ID card for voters. Not mandatory for voting — voters can use alternative IDs (passport, Aadhaar, etc.). Voter enrollment is mandatory for participation; EPIC is the primary proof. / EPIC (Voter ID): introduced 1993 by T.N. Seshan/ECI."),
    (2,"medium","NRIs ఏ year vote కి eligible అయ్యారు? / From which year are NRIs eligible to vote?",
     "2000","2010 — Representation of People (Amendment) Act 2010 gave NRIs (Non-Resident Indians) the right to vote; NRI must be enrolled as voter in constituency where their name appears in voter list at their address in India; must come to India to vote (postal ballot later introduced)","2014","2003","b",
     "NRI voting rights: RPA (Amendment) Act 2010. Non-Resident Indians who are citizens of India can enroll as voters in their home constituency (where their name is in voter roll at their India address). Originally had to come to India to vote; later amendments and ECI pilot programs for postal ballot for NRI voters. / NRI voting: 2010 amendment to RPA; enroll in home constituency; must come to India to vote (postal ballot later)."),
    (2,"hard","Single-member vs multi-member constituency ఏ difference? / What is the difference between single-member and multi-member constituencies?",
     "No difference","Single-member: 1 seat, 1 winner — all LS and most State Assembly constituencies; Multi-member: 2 seats, 2 winners — previously existed in India; now mostly abolished (retained in some J&K areas); UK Parliamentary constituencies are single-member","Multi-member only for SC/ST","Multi-member for RS","b",
     "Single-member constituency: One seat per constituency; first-past-the-post system — candidate with most votes wins. All LS constituencies are single-member. Most State Assembly constituencies are single-member. Multi-member constituencies (two seats per constituency) previously existed in India — abolished over time. Currently mostly single-member system. / Single-member: 1 winner per constituency — all LS constituencies; Multi-member: was historically in some state assemblies (now mostly abolished)."),
    (2,"easy","Electoral roll revision ఏ time period? / When is the electoral roll revised?",
     "Only before general elections","Annual revision — electoral rolls are revised annually; special drives between August-November; Summary Revision in October-November; Intensive Revision every 5 years; voters can enroll throughout year; rolls finalized before elections","Only when PM orders","Every 10 years","b",
     "Electoral roll revision: ECI revises rolls annually. Special Summary Revision: October-November (qualifying date January 1). Intensive Revision: every 5 years (before major elections). Continuous enrollment: citizens can enroll throughout year. ECI freezes rolls 30 days before voting for any election. / Electoral roll: annual revision; Special Summary (Oct-Nov); qualified date January 1."),

    # Section 3: Conduct of Elections (RPA 1951) (8)
    (3,"easy","RPA 1951 ఏమిటి? / What is the Representation of People Act 1951?",
     "Law on political parties","Primary legislation for conduct of elections — governs: qualification/disqualification of candidates; conduct of elections; corrupt practices (Sec.123); election offences; disputes; election petitions","Law on voting age","ECI establishment","b",
     "RPA 1951 (Representation of People Act 1951): Primary election law. Governs: (1) Qualification and disqualification of candidates; (2) Conduct of elections; (3) Corrupt practices (Sec.123); (4) Election offences; (5) Election petitions and disputes; (6) Delimitation (partially). Art.327 empowers Parliament to pass this Act. / RPA 1951: primary election law — candidate qualification/disqualification, corrupt practices, election petitions."),
    (3,"medium","Corrupt practice Sec.123 RPA ఏమి include చేస్తుంది? / What is included as corrupt practice under Sec.123 RPA?",
     "Only bribery","Multiple: (1) Bribery; (2) Undue influence; (3) False statement about candidate's personal character; (4) Hiring vehicles for voters; (5) Booth capturing; (6) Use of government machinery for election; (7) Religious/caste-based appeals that promote enmity","Only physical violence","Only vote buying","b",
     "Corrupt practices under Sec.123 RPA 1951: (1) Bribery — giving/offering gratification to voters; (2) Undue influence — intimidation; (3) Personation at polling; (4) False statements about candidates; (5) Hiring vehicles for voters (within 2km of polling station); (6) Incurring unauthorized election expenditure; (7) Use of government machinery/resources; (8) Religious/caste appeals promoting enmity. Finding = election void. / Sec.123 corrupt practices: bribery, undue influence, false statements, vehicle hiring, govt machinery use, religious/caste appeals."),
    (3,"easy","Election petition ఏ court లో file చేయాలి? / In which court must an election petition be filed?",
     "District Court","High Court — LS and State Assembly election petitions filed before High Court; Presidential and Vice-Presidential election petitions before Supreme Court; must be filed within 45 days of result declaration","Supreme Court directly","ECI","b",
     "Election petition: (1) LS and State Assembly elections → filed before High Court of the State; (2) Presidential election → filed before Supreme Court; (3) Vice-Presidential election → filed before Supreme Court. Must be filed within 45 days of result declaration (or date of notification of election). / Election petition: LS/Assembly → HC; Presidential/VP → SC; within 45 days of result."),
    (3,"medium","Election petition ground ఏమిటి? / What are the grounds for an election petition?",
     "Any political reason","Corrupt practice (Sec.123) + Improper rejection/acceptance of nomination + Improper counting of votes + Non-compliance with election rules materially affecting result + Candidate not qualified + Excessive expenditure","Personal dispute","Only vote rigging","b",
     "Election petition grounds: (1) Corrupt practice by returned candidate/his agent; (2) Improper rejection of a valid nomination; (3) Improper acceptance of an invalid nomination; (4) Improper counting of votes; (5) Non-compliance with provisions of Constitution or law materially affecting result; (6) Returned candidate was not qualified or was disqualified. / Election petition grounds: corrupt practice + improper nomination + improper counting + non-compliance + unqualified candidate."),
    (3,"hard","Boona Narsaiah Goud v. Jalagam Vengal Rao case ఏమిటి? / What principle does the law of election disputes follow?",
     "Election is always valid","Elections presumed valid unless proved otherwise — Court upholds election unless petitioner proves grounds of challenge; burden of proof on petitioner; strict rules of pleading — ground must be specifically pleaded in petition; cannot raise new grounds in oral argument","Election always void","Only criminal standards","b",
     "Election dispute principle: Elections are presumed valid. Petitioner (the challenger) bears the full burden of proof. Rules of election petitions are strict: (1) Every ground of challenge must be specifically pleaded in the written petition; (2) Cannot raise new grounds during oral argument; (3) Standard is civil standard (balance of probabilities); (4) Courts are reluctant to set aside elections due to impact on democratic process. / Election petition: burden on petitioner; specific pleading required; elections presumed valid."),
    (3,"easy","Election schedule ఏ elements ఉంటాయి? / What does the election schedule include?",
     "Only polling day","Notification date → Last date for nominations → Scrutiny of nominations → Last date for withdrawal → Polling date(s) → Counting date → Result declaration","Only counting","Only MCC start","b",
     "Election schedule sequence: (1) Issue of election notification; (2) Last date for filing nominations (minimum 7 days from notification); (3) Scrutiny of nominations (next day after last date); (4) Last date for withdrawal (2 days after scrutiny); (5) Polling date(s); (6) Counting of votes; (7) Declaration of results. MCC operative from election schedule announcement. / Election schedule: notification → nominations → scrutiny → withdrawal → polling → counting → results."),
    (3,"medium","ఎన్నికల పిటిషన్ కు 45 రోజుల గడువు ఎందుకు? / Why is there a 45-day limitation for election petitions?",
     "Arbitrary decision","To ensure certainty in governance — if election disputes could be filed indefinitely, elected members would remain in legal uncertainty for their entire term; 45 days provides reasonable time to gather evidence while ensuring governance can proceed with certainty","ECI preference","International standard","b",
     "45-day limitation rationale: (1) Governance certainty — elected representative must know their position is secure to function effectively; (2) Encourages prompt challenge — parties can't wait and file petition strategically; (3) Evidence is fresh in early period; (4) Balance between right to challenge and governance stability. SC has strictly enforced this limitation (condoned only in exceptional cases). / 45 days: balances right to challenge with governance certainty; encourages prompt filing."),
    (3,"hard","Election petition లో recrimination petition అంటే ఏమిటి? / What is a recrimination petition in an election petition?",
     "Petition by ECI","Respondent (winning candidate) files cross-petition against petitioner claiming petitioner himself committed corrupt practices","Counter-affidavit","Third party intervention","b",
     "Recrimination petition (Sec.97 RPA 1951): When an election petition is filed against a returned candidate, the respondent can file a recrimination petition claiming the petitioner (or petitioner's candidate) also committed corrupt practices. If recrimination succeeds, petitioner's candidate's election can also be voided. / Recrimination: Sec.97 RPA — respondent can counter-challenge petitioner's conduct."),

    # Section 4: EVM and VVPAT (8)
    (4,"easy","EVM ఏ year first use చేయబడింది? / In which year was EVM first used?",
     "1980","1982 — First limited use in Paravur constituency, Kerala by-election in 1982; full nationwide use from 2004 General Elections","1990","2000","b",
     "EVM first use: 1982 (limited trial — Paravur constituency, North Paravur, Kerala Assembly by-election). Nationwide use: 2004 General Elections (18th Lok Sabha elections). EVM manufactured by BEL (Bharat Electronics Limited, Bangalore) and ECIL (Electronics Corporation of India Limited, Hyderabad). / EVM: first 1982 (Kerala by-election); nationwide 2004."),
    (4,"medium","EVM advantages ఏమిటి? / What are the advantages of EVMs?",
     "More expensive","(1) Reduces booth capturing — no ballot box stuffing; (2) Reduces invalid votes (no chance to spoil ballot); (3) Fast counting — results in hours; (4) Tamper-evident; (5) Saves paper; (6) Reduces polling staff fatigue; (7) Can be used in remote areas without electricity (battery-operated)","Only for cities","More complicated to use","b",
     "EVM advantages: (1) Reduces booth capturing (ballot box stuffing); (2) No invalid/rejected votes; (3) Faster counting (results in hours vs days); (4) Paper saving; (5) Battery-operated — works without electricity; (6) Tamper-evident seals; (7) No ballot paper fatigue for voters/staff; (8) Cleaner, simpler process. EVM also prevents fraud through sequential pressing — each button only registers once. / EVM advantages: no booth capturing, no invalid votes, fast counting, battery-operated, paper saving."),
    (4,"easy","EVM manufacture companies ఏమిటి? / Which companies manufacture EVMs?",
     "DRDO only","BEL (Bharat Electronics Limited, Bangalore) and ECIL (Electronics Corporation of India Limited, Hyderabad) — both are public sector undertakings (PSUs) under Government of India","Private companies","Import from USA","b",
     "EVM manufacturers: (1) BEL — Bharat Electronics Limited, Bangalore (Ministry of Defence); (2) ECIL — Electronics Corporation of India Limited, Hyderabad (Department of Atomic Energy). Both are Indian PSUs. ECI orders EVMs from these two companies exclusively. No private or foreign manufacture. / EVM: made by BEL (Bangalore) + ECIL (Hyderabad) — both Indian PSUs."),
    (4,"medium","VVPAT ఏమిటి? / What is VVPAT?",
     "Virtual Voting Processing and Tallying","Voter-Verifiable Paper Audit Trail — paper slip printer attached to EVM; after voter presses candidate button on EVM, VVPAT prints a slip showing candidate name and symbol; slip visible through glass window for 7 seconds then drops into sealed box","Video Voting Protocol and Technology","Very Verified Paper Account Transaction","b",
     "VVPAT (Voter-Verifiable Paper Audit Trail): Printer attached to EVM. After voter presses vote button: (1) EVM records vote electronically; (2) VVPAT prints a slip with candidate name, symbol, serial number; (3) Voter can see the slip through glass window for 7 seconds; (4) Slip drops into sealed box automatically. Purpose: allows voters to verify their vote was registered correctly. / VVPAT: paper slip showing candidate name + symbol for 7 seconds after voting; voter can verify; then sealed."),
    (4,"easy","VVPAT first use ఏ year? / In which year was VVPAT first used?",
     "2010","2013 — First used in Noksen constituency, Nagaland Assembly by-election (September 2013); full use in 2019 General Elections (all constituencies)","2016","2004","b",
     "VVPAT first use: September 2013 (Noksen constituency, Nagaland Assembly by-election). ECI pilot under CEC V.S. Sampath. Used in 5 states in 2014 elections. Nationwide use (all LS constituencies): 2019 General Elections. SC: VVPAT slips must be counted in 5 randomly selected booths per constituency. / VVPAT: first 2013 (Nagaland, Noksen); nationwide 2019."),
    (4,"medium","SC VVPAT count ruling ఏమిటి? / What did the SC rule about VVPAT slip counting?",
     "100% VVPAT counting","5 randomly selected booths per constituency — SC in N. Chandrasekaran v. Union of India (2019): VVPAT slips must be counted in 5 randomly selected booths (polling stations) per Assembly constituency (for LS) or per segment (for State); not 100% counting","No VVPAT counting needed","ECI decides","b",
     "SC VVPAT ruling (2019): N. Chandrasekaran v. Union of India. SC increased the number of VVPAT slips to be counted from 1 to 5 per Assembly segment per constituency. This was increased from ECI's practice of 1 per constituency. SC rejected demand for 100% counting. ECI followed in 2019 and 2024 elections. In 2024, SC again dismissed demand for full VVPAT count (ADR v. ECI). / SC 2019: 5 VVPAT slips counted per constituency; 2024: SC dismissed 100% VVPAT demand."),
    (4,"hard","EVM hacking claims ఏమి held by courts? / What have courts held about EVM hacking claims?",
     "EVMs are hackable","EVMs are standalone machines — SC has consistently held that EVMs are not connected to internet; cannot be hacked remotely; standalone machines; ECI has shown EVM challenge events where nobody successfully demonstrated hacking; SC dismissed petitions demanding return to paper ballots","EVMs need replacement","Courts undecided","b",
     "EVM and courts: (1) SC has repeatedly upheld EVMs as secure and tamper-proof; (2) EVMs are standalone (not internet-connected) machines; (3) ECI has held public EVM challenge events — no successful hack demonstrated; (4) 2024 ADR case: SC upheld EVM + VVPAT process; dismissed demand for paper ballots or 100% VVPAT count; (5) Several PILs dismissed. Courts consistently support EVMs with VVPAT as sufficient safeguard. / EVMs: courts consistently upheld as secure; standalone; no internet connection; SC dismissed hacking claims."),
    (4,"easy","EVM ని internet connect చేయవచ్చా? / Can EVMs be connected to the internet?",
     "Yes — for counting","No — EVMs are standalone machines; no wireless/internet capability; voting unit, control unit, VVPAT are connected only to each other; no external network connection; this is a key security feature","Only during counting","Only for transmission","b",
     "EVMs are standalone: No internet, Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, or any wireless connectivity. EVMs consist of: (1) Ballot Unit (voter presses button); (2) Control Unit (presiding officer controls, counts); (3) VVPAT (paper slip). These three are connected to each other only. No external network. This prevents remote hacking. / EVM: standalone; no internet/wireless; only Ballot Unit + Control Unit + VVPAT connected to each other."),

    # Section 5: Qualifications and Disqualifications (8)
    (5,"easy","LS member minimum age ఏమిటి? / What is the minimum age for Lok Sabha membership?",
     "18 years","25 years — Art.84(b): person must be not less than 25 years of age to be eligible for election to Lok Sabha","21 years","30 years","b",
     "Lok Sabha qualification: Art.84(b) — must be at least 25 years old. (Rajya Sabha: 30 years; President: 35 years.) Also: must be citizen of India; must be on electoral roll; must subscribe to oath (Schedule III); must not be disqualified under Art.102. / LS member: minimum 25 years (Art.84(b))."),
    (5,"medium","Office of profit ఏమిటి? / What is 'Office of Profit' in disqualification context?",
     "Private business","Government office that carries financial gain — Art.102(1)(a): holding an 'office of profit' under Union or State Government (other than Minister or office exempted by Parliament/State Legislature) disqualifies a person from Parliament membership; prevents conflicts of interest","Only IAS position","Only board directorship","b",
     "Office of Profit (Art.102(1)(a)): A person holding an office of profit under Central or State Government (other than Minister — which is excluded) is disqualified from being a member of Parliament. Purpose: prevents legislators from holding government appointments that could conflict with their legislative duties or give government undue influence over them. Parliament/State Legislature can exempt specific offices. / Office of profit: Govt office with financial gain → disqualification (except Ministers + exempted offices)."),
    (5,"easy","President election కి ఏ qualification కావాలి? / What qualifications are required to contest the Presidential election?",
     "Only Indian citizen","Indian citizen, 35+ years, qualified to be elected to Lok Sabha, not hold any office of profit under Govt — Art.58: President's qualification","35 years + LS qualification","30 years + RS qualification","c",
     "Presidential qualification (Art.58): (1) Citizen of India; (2) Has completed 35 years; (3) Is qualified for election as a member of Lok Sabha; (4) Shall not hold any office of profit under Govt of India or any State. / President: 35+ years + eligible for LS + citizen + no office of profit."),
    (5,"medium","Lily Thomas case (2013) ఏ held? / What did Lily Thomas v. Union of India (2013) hold?",
     "Reservation in judiciary","Convicted sitting MPs/MLAs immediately disqualified from membership — Sec.8(4) RPA 1951 (which allowed convicted sitting members to continue pending appeal) was declared unconstitutional; conviction + 2+ year sentence → immediate disqualification; cannot continue in office even during appeal","Electoral bonds valid","VVPAT mandatory","b",
     "Lily Thomas v. Union of India (2013): SC struck down Sec.8(4) RPA 1951. Sec.8(4) allowed a sitting MP/MLA convicted of a criminal offence and sentenced to 2+ years to continue in office while their appeal was pending. SC held: Sec.8(4) is unconstitutional — Art.102/191 mandates immediate disqualification upon conviction and sentence; Parliament cannot protect sitting members differently from others. / Lily Thomas 2013: convicted + 2+ years sentence → sitting MP/MLA immediately disqualified (can't continue pending appeal)."),
    (5,"hard","Rajya Sabha ordinary resident requirement ఏమి changed? / What changed about the 'ordinary resident' requirement for Rajya Sabha?",
     "More strict requirement","Requirement removed — originally RS candidate had to be ordinary resident of the state from which contesting; Representation of People (Amendment) Act 2003 removed this requirement; now a person can contest RS election from any state where enrolled as voter","Never existed","SC struck it down","b",
     "RS ordinary resident requirement: Originally, a person had to be an ordinary resident of the State from which they contested the RS election. Representation of People (Amendment) Act 2003 removed this requirement. Now: anyone enrolled as a voter anywhere in India can contest RS election from any State. This change enabled political leaders to contest from states other than their home state. / RS 2003 change: ordinary resident requirement removed; can contest from any state if enrolled as voter anywhere."),
    (5,"easy","నామినేట్ అయిన సభ్యులు Presidential election లో ఓటు వేయగలరా? / Can nominated members of Parliament vote in the Presidential election?",
     "Yes always","No — only elected members can vote; Art.54: Electoral College for Presidential election = elected members of LS + RS + elected members of State Legislative Assemblies; nominated members (12 RS + 2 LS Anglo-Indians before 2020) NOT included","Only in hung parliament","Only if PM approves","b",
     "Presidential Electoral College: Art.54 specifies ELECTED members only: (1) Elected members of both Houses of Parliament (LS + RS); (2) Elected members of Legislative Assemblies of all States (including Delhi + Puducherry). Nominated members (RS has 12 nominated; LS had 2 Anglo-Indian nominated before 2020) are NOT in Presidential Electoral College. / Presidential Election: only elected members (not nominated); Art.54 Electoral College."),
    (5,"medium","Disqualification on mental incapacity ఏమిటి? / What disqualification exists for mental incapacity?",
     "No such disqualification","Art.102(1)(b): person is disqualified if declared to be of unsound mind by a court of competent jurisdiction — person declared unsound mind (lunatic) cannot be a member of Parliament; similar provision in Art.191 for State Legislature","Only if not functioning","Only for RS members","b",
     "Mental incapacity disqualification: Art.102(1)(b): Person declared to be of unsound mind by a competent court is disqualified from being an MP. Art.191(1)(b): Same for MLAs. This ensures lawmakers must be mentally competent to discharge their duties. Person must be declared unsound by a court — mere mental health issues without court order insufficient. / Art.102(1)(b): declared unsound mind by court → disqualified from Parliament; Art.191 same for MLAs."),
    (5,"hard","Double membership ఏ rules ఉన్నాయి Parliament లో? / What rules exist about double membership in Parliament?",
     "Allowed freely","Not allowed — person cannot be a member of both Houses of Parliament simultaneously; Sec.68 RPA 1951: if elected to both LS and RS, must vacate one within a specified period; similarly cannot be MP and MLA simultaneously; if MP elected to State Assembly, must resign Parliamentary seat","Always allowed","Only for Ministers","b",
     "Double membership prohibition: (1) Cannot be member of both LS and RS simultaneously; (2) If elected to both, must choose and vacate one (Sec.68 RPA 1951) — within 10 days; (3) Cannot be MP and MLA simultaneously — Sec.9A RPA 1951; if sitting MLA gets elected as MP, must vacate MLA seat within 14 days; (4) Exception: can be MP while being member of State Council (legislative council) — both can be held as MLC is indirectly elected. / Double membership: cannot hold LS + RS; cannot hold MP + MLA; election to one requires vacating other."),

    # Section 6: Election Expenditure (8)
    (6,"easy","LS election expenditure limit ఎంత? / What is the election expenditure limit for a Lok Sabha candidate?",
     "Rs.25 lakh","Rs.95 lakh (large states) — ECI revised limits in 2022; larger states: Rs.95 lakh per candidate; smaller states/UTs: Rs.75 lakh per LS candidate; State Assembly: Rs.40 lakh (large) or Rs.28 lakh (small) per candidate","Rs.1 crore always","No limit","b",
     "Election expenditure limits (ECI, 2022 revision): Lok Sabha candidates: Rs.95 lakh (large states like UP, Maharashtra, Bihar) or Rs.75 lakh (smaller states/UTs). State Assembly candidates: Rs.40 lakh (large states) or Rs.28 lakh (smaller states). Candidate must maintain accounts and file expenditure statement within 30 days of election result. / LS expenditure limit: Rs.95 lakh (large states); Rs.75 lakh (small states/UTs)."),
    (6,"medium","Election expenditure account ఎప్పుడు file చేయాలి? / Within what time must a candidate file their election expenditure account?",
     "Within 7 days","Within 30 days of election result declaration — Section 78 RPA 1951: candidate must lodge their account of election expenses with District Election Officer within 30 days of results; failure → possible disqualification","Within 90 days","Within 1 year","b",
     "Section 78 RPA 1951: Candidate must lodge account of election expenses with District Election Officer within 30 days of the date of publication of election results. Failure to file account within time can lead to disqualification of the candidate for 3 years. ECI enforces this strictly. / Sec.78 RPA: candidate files expenditure account within 30 days of result."),
    (6,"easy","Party's total election expenditure ఏ limit ఉంది? / What is the limit on a party's total election expenditure?",
     "Rs.100 crore per party","No legal ceiling on party's overall election spending — only individual candidates have expenditure limits; political parties can spend unlimited amounts on election campaigns (advertisements, rallies, etc.) on behalf of party (not individual candidates); Electoral Bonds (struck down 2024) was one channel","Rs.10 crore per state","Same as candidate limit","b",
     "Party election expenditure: No legal ceiling. Individual candidate: Rs.95 lakh (LS, large states). But the PARTY can spend unlimited amounts on: party advertisements, events, campaigns — as long as it's for the party, not for a specific candidate (candidate's account is separate). This is a significant loophole in election finance law. / Party: no expenditure ceiling; individual candidates: Rs.95 lakh (LS); party expenses not counted in candidate limit."),
    (6,"medium","Paid news ఏమిటి? / What is 'paid news' in election context?",
     "Newspaper paid for by ECI","Political advertising disguised as news coverage — candidates/parties pay newspapers/TV channels to publish/broadcast favorable content as news (not labeled as advertisement); ECI has guidelines prohibiting this; counted as election expenditure if discovered; penalty: disqualification","ECI advertisements","Party publications","b",
     "Paid news: Political candidates/parties pay media to publish/broadcast favorable content disguised as genuine news coverage (not as paid advertisement). Misleads voters. ECI: (1) Monitoring cell to track paid news; (2) Treating paid news as election expenditure of candidate; (3) Show-cause notices to candidates; (4) Can lead to disqualification if expenditure limit exceeded. Press Council of India also takes cognizance. / Paid news: political advertising disguised as news; ECI treats as candidate expenditure; penalty for violation."),
    (6,"hard","Expenditure limit violation ఏ consequence? / What are the consequences of violating election expenditure limits?",
     "Only fine","Multiple consequences: (1) Election can be declared void on election petition (if violation is 'corrupt practice' under Sec.123(6) — incurring unauthorized expenses); (2) Candidate can be disqualified for 3 years (Sec.10A RPA — failure to lodge accounts); (3) Criminal prosecution for corrupt practice","Only warning","Only disqualification from that election","b",
     "Expenditure violation consequences: (1) Corrupt practice (Sec.123(6)): incurring unauthorized election expenses → election can be voided on election petition; (2) Failure to lodge account (Sec.78): candidate can be disqualified for 3 years from contesting elections (Sec.10A RPA 1951); (3) Criminal offences under Sec.171H IPC (electoral offences). / Expenditure violation: election void (corrupt practice) + 3-year disqualification (Sec.10A) for failure to file accounts."),
    (6,"easy","Exit poll ban ఏమిటి? / When are exit polls banned in India?",
     "Always banned","Exit polls banned from voting start until last phase voting ends — Sec.126A RPA 1951: no person shall conduct, publish, or disseminate exit polls and opinion poll results during the period commencing from voting and until last phase voting ends; violation = criminal offence","Never banned","Only for LS elections","b",
     "Exit poll ban (Sec.126A RPA 1951): Exit polls (surveys of voters as they leave polling booths) cannot be published or broadcast from the time polling begins for the first phase until the last phase of voting ends. Multi-phase elections: ban operative throughout voting period across phases. Reason: exit polls could influence voters in later phases. Violation: imprisonment up to 2 years or fine or both. / Exit polls: banned from voting start to last phase end (Sec.126A RPA); prevents influence on multi-phase elections."),
    (6,"medium","MCC operative ఏ period? / For what period is the Model Code of Conduct operative?",
     "Only polling day","From election schedule announcement to result declaration — MCC is operative from the moment ECI announces the election schedule (press conference); ceases after election results declared; covers: campaign conduct, use of govt machinery, new schemes/announcements by ruling party","Only during counting","Only 2 days before polling","b",
     "MCC period: From ECI announcement of election schedule → until results declared. During this period: (1) Ruling party cannot announce new welfare schemes; (2) Government machinery cannot be used for campaigns; (3) No use of government buildings for party events; (4) No new appointments by virtue of position (discretionary); (5) Campaign and speech rules apply. / MCC: from schedule announcement to result declaration; restricts ruling party and all parties."),
    (6,"hard","Election finance reform suggestions ఏమిటి? / What are the main suggestions for election finance reform?",
     "Abolish all limits","State funding of elections + lower donation disclosure threshold + party finance transparency + RTI for parties + cap on party expenditure + electoral bonds reform (now struck down) — ECI, Law Commission (255th Report 2015), ADR have recommended comprehensive reforms","No changes needed","Only increase limits","b",
     "Election finance reform suggestions (ECI, 255th Law Commission Report 2015, ADR): (1) State funding of elections; (2) Lower disclosure threshold (from Rs.20,000 to Rs.2,000); (3) Making parties RTI public authorities; (4) Cap on party election expenditure; (5) Transparent party accounts; (6) Banning corporate donations; (7) Stricter paid news monitoring; (8) NOTA to have effect; (9) Electoral bonds (now struck down). / Election finance reform: state funding + lower disclosure threshold + party transparency + party expenditure cap."),

    # Section 7: Key Facts (8)
    (7,"easy","61st Amendment 1988 ఏ change చేసింది? / What did the 61st Amendment 1988 change?",
     "Anti-defection law","Reduced voting age from 21 to 18 years — 61st Constitutional Amendment Act 1988 amended Art.326; effective December 28, 1988; PM Rajiv Gandhi government","ECI composition","Electoral bonds","b",
     "61st Constitutional Amendment 1988: Reduced voting age for LS and State Assembly elections from 21 to 18 years. Amended Art.326. Effective December 28, 1988. PM Rajiv Gandhi's government. Added ~4 crore new voters. Democratized participation by including youth. / 61st Amendment 1988: voting age 21 → 18 (Art.326)."),
    (7,"medium","Sukumar Sen ఎవరు? / Who was Sukumar Sen?",
     "First CM of Bengal","First Chief Election Commissioner of India (1950-1958) — conducted India's first two General Elections (1952 and 1957); celebrated for organizing elections for massive, largely illiterate population; pictorial ballot system for illiterate voters","First CEC of India","First CJI","c",
     "Sukumar Sen: First Chief Election Commissioner of India (1950-1958). Conducted 1st General Elections (October 1951 – February 1952) and 2nd General Elections (1957). Challenge: over 17 crore voters, mostly illiterate. Solution: pictorial symbols on ballot papers and ballot boxes. Internationally acclaimed for successful democratic elections. / Sukumar Sen: first CEC (1950-58); conducted 1st and 2nd General Elections."),
